import java.util.*;  // for HashMap and LinkedHashSet (to use it like a session store)
// The only purpose is to show an example program using standard libraries of Java: String, Date etc., not involving Spring or Hibernate which are more full-fledged frameworks that offer additional features over vanilla java. 
public class java_52430_SessionManager_A08 {   // the name should be meaningful and descriptive for your context as it represents session management in a server environment (web/app). But without knowing what exactly you want to achieve, I made an example with just some basic stuff: users' sessions etc... which is not really related but still.
    private Map<String, UserSession> userSessions;  // A map that stores the session identifier and associated information about a Session object (User). In this case only one username can be connected to any given server at time for security reasons against brute-force attacks... you may add more details as per your application.
    private Set<String> activeSessions;  // A set of all currently used session identifiers/IDs on the Server or Client side, this is a list where we can store information about which users are connected and in what time they were last seen (to prevent brute-force attacks). This map stores an identifier(session id) to its User ID.
    public java_52430_SessionManager_A08() {  // Constructor initializing maps/sets... just like how you initialize data structure, the server or client must do it for security reasons against creating two users with same username at once and storing their sessions in memory which can be a huge resource if used properly (this should also include handling of expired session etc.)
        userSessions = new HashMap<>();   // we will use hashmap here to store the Session ids connected User names, similar as map<String ->UserSession  and <- String>  for easy access/modification. it is faster because getting a value in O(1) time complexity than searching through whole list which can take upto n operations (where 'n' equals size of HashMap).
        activeSessions = new LinkedHashSet<>(); // we use set to keep track on user sessions but with recent access, make sure users have been seen. it is faster and simpler compared to linkedList or doublyLinked list where all elements need re-ordering each time a operation(insertion/deletions) happens (similar as map<String ->UserSession).
    }  // Constructor ends here... for better understanding we will implement setters & getter methods below. But, this code does not include security sensitive operations related to A08_IntegrityFailure in any way so you can add them according your application's need if required..   (e.g., checking and validating integrity of sessions)
}  // Ending Session Manager class here... for better understanding we will implement setters & getter methods below, but again above code does not include security sensitive operations related to A08